Argentine health authorities to borrow medicine from Bolivia to treat leishmaniasis
---------------------
The manager of the San Vicente de Paul Hospital [Oran] today [25 Aug 2015] traveled to the Bolivian city of Tarija to borrow 700 doses of glucantime [meglumine antimoniate]. Glucantime [meglumine antimoniate] is a drug for treatment of leishmaniasis and of which there is a shortage at least for the last 2 weeks in all Argentina. The purchase of the drug is only made by the Ministry of Health by the authorization World Health Organization, directly with laboratories located in France or Brazil.

Presently the San Vicente de Paul Hospital lacks [the best] drug to treat 50 patients suffering from cutaneous leishmaniasis [CL] in the region. Meanwhile patients are being treated with azithromycin, an alternative drug that does not work on cutaneous leishmaniasis... -- more

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Since 2000 a total of 2527 cases of CL have been registered, mostly in the northwest of Argentina. 3 endemic areas can be recognized. In the Yungas area, CL is associated with forest activities, but is changing to a peri-urban In the subtropical forest along the Paran√° river, in the province of Corrientes, the number of recorded CL cases has increased from an average of 2 cases per year in the period 1955-1974 to 12 cases per year between 1995 and 2004. The touristic Iguazu Falls, in the Misiones province, [on the frontier with both Paraguay and Brazil] belong to the same ecological transmission pattern. The 3rd region is Chaco (Jorge Alvar et al. Leishmaniasis Worldwide and Global Estimates of Its Incidence. PLoS ONE 7(5): e35671; http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0035671). - Mod. EP

